  16. (** Ephemerons and weak hash tables.

  18.     Ephemerons and weak hash tables are useful when one wants to cache
  19.     or memorize the computation of a function, as long as the
  20.     arguments and the function are used, without creating memory leaks
  21.     by continuously keeping old computation results that are not
  22.     useful anymore because one argument or the function is freed. An
  23.     implementation using {!Hashtbl.t} is not suitable because all
  24.     associations would keep the arguments and the result in memory.

  26.     Ephemerons can also be used for "adding" a field to an arbitrary
  27.     boxed OCaml value: you can attach some information to a value
  28.     created by an external library without memory leaks.

  30.     Ephemerons hold some keys and one or no data. They are all boxed
  31.     OCaml values. The keys of an ephemeron have the same behavior
  32.     as weak pointers according to the garbage collector. In fact
  33.     OCaml weak pointers are implemented as ephemerons without data.

  35.     The keys and data of an ephemeron are said to be full if they
  36.     point to a value, or empty if the value has never been set, has
  37.     been unset, or was erased by the GC. In the function that accesses
  38.     the keys or data these two states are represented by the [option]
  39.     type.

  41.     The data is considered by the garbage collector alive if all the
  42.     full keys are alive and if the ephemeron is alive. When one of the
  43.     keys is not considered alive anymore by the GC, the data is
  44.     emptied from the ephemeron. The data could be alive for another
  45.     reason and in that case the GC will not free it, but the ephemeron
  46.     will not hold the data anymore.

  48.     The ephemerons complicate the notion of liveness of values, because
  49.     it is not anymore an equivalence with the reachability from root
  50.     value by usual pointers (not weak and not ephemerons). With ephemerons
  51.     the notion of liveness is constructed by the least fixpoint of:
  52.        A value is alive if:
  53.         - it is a root value
  54.         - it is reachable from alive value by usual pointers
  55.         - it is the data of an alive ephemeron with all its full keys alive

  57.     Notes:
  58.     - All the types defined in this module cannot be marshaled
  59.     using {!Stdlib.output_value} or the functions of the
  60.     {!Marshal} module.

  62.     Ephemerons are defined in a language agnostic way in this paper:
  63.     B. Hayes, Ephemerons: A New Finalization Mechanism, OOPSLA'97

  65.     @since 4.03
  66. *)

  68. (** {b Unsynchronized accesses} *)

  70. [@@@alert unsynchronized_access
  71.   "Unsynchronized accesses to weak hash tables are a programming error."
  72. ]

  74. (**
  75.     Unsynchronized accesses to a weak hash table may lead to an invalid
  76.     weak hash table state. Thus, concurrent accesses to a buffer must be
  77.     synchronized (for instance with a {!Mutex.t}).
  78. *)

  80. module type S = sig
  81.   (** Propose the same interface as usual hash table. However since
  82.       the bindings are weak, even if [mem h k] is true, a subsequent
  83.       [find h k] may raise [Not_found] because the garbage collector
  84.       can run between the two.
  85.   *)

  148. module K1 : sig
  149.   type ('k,'d) t (** an ephemeron with one key *)

  151.   val make : 'k -> 'd -> ('k,'d) t
  152.   (** [Ephemeron.K1.make k d] creates an ephemeron with key [k] and data [d]. *)

  154.   val query : ('k,'d) t -> 'k -> 'd option
  155.   (** [Ephemeron.K1.query eph key] returns [Some x] (where [x] is the
  156.       ephemeron's data) if [key] is physically equal to [eph]'s key, and
  157.       [None] if [eph] is empty or [key] is not equal to [eph]'s key. *)

  159.   module Make (H:Hashtbl.HashedType) : S with type key = H.t
  160.   (** Functor building an implementation of a weak hash table *)

  162.   module MakeSeeded (H:Hashtbl.SeededHashedType) : SeededS with type key = H.t
  163.   (** Functor building an implementation of a weak hash table.
  164.       The seed is similar to the one of {!Hashtbl.MakeSeeded}. *)

  166.   module Bucket : sig

  168.     type ('k, 'd) t
  169.     (** A bucket is a mutable "list" of ephemerons. *)

  171.     val make : unit -> ('k, 'd) t
  172.     (** Create a new bucket. *)

  174.     val add : ('k, 'd) t -> 'k -> 'd -> unit
  175.     (** Add an ephemeron to the bucket. *)

  177.     val remove : ('k, 'd) t -> 'k -> unit
  178.     (** [remove b k] removes from [b] the most-recently added
  179.         ephemeron with key [k], or does nothing if there is no such
  180.         ephemeron. *)

  182.     val find : ('k, 'd) t -> 'k -> 'd option
  183.     (** Returns the data of the most-recently added ephemeron with the
  184.         given key, or [None] if there is no such ephemeron. *)

  186.     val length : ('k, 'd) t -> int
  187.     (** Returns an upper bound on the length of the bucket. *)

  189.     val clear : ('k, 'd) t -> unit
  190.     (** Remove all ephemerons from the bucket. *)

  192.   end

  194. end
